.SH INSTALLATION (DOCKER CONTAINER)
An official debos container is available:
.IP
.EX
docker pull godebos/debos
.EE
.PP
Debos needs virtualization to be enabled on the host and shared with the
container.
.PP
Check that \f[CR]kvm\f[R] is enabled and writable by the user running
the docker container by running \f[CR]ls /dev/kvm\f[R]
.SS CONTAINER USAGE
.RS
.PP
This container should be used as an executable, i.e.\ there is no need
to add \f[CR]debos\f[R] after \f[CR]godebos/debos\f[R].
.RE
.PP
To build \f[CR]recipe.yaml\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
cd <PATH_TO_RECIPE_DIR>
docker run \-\-rm \-it \-\-device /dev/kvm \-\-user $(id \-u) \-\-workdir /recipes \-\-mount \(dqtype=bind,source=$(pwd),destination=/recipes\(dq \-\-security\-opt label=disable godebos/debos <RECIPE.yaml>
.EE
.PP
If debos fails to run the KVM fakemachine backend and the
\f[CR]/dev/kvm\f[R] device exists on your host, you may need to add the
owning group of the device as a supplementary group of the container.
This will work if \f[CR]ls \-l /dev/kvm\f[R] indicates that the owning
group has read\-write access to the device.
Adding the supplementary group may be unsafe depending on the owning
group of \f[CR]/dev/kvm\f[R], but it could be required depending on your
login provider.
To add the group, add
\f[CR]\-\-group\-add \(dq$(stat \-c \(aq%g\(aq /dev/kvm)\(dq\f[R] to
your \f[CR]docker run\f[R] command before \f[CR]godebos/debos\f[R].
See \c
.UR https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/run/#additional-groups
Docker run reference \(en Additional Groups
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.SS CONTAINER BUILD
To build the debos container image from current git branch:
.IP
.EX
docker build \-t godebos/debos .
.EE
.SH USING DEBOS IN GITHUB ACTIONS
debos can be run in GitHub Actions using the official container with KVM
support for isolated and reproducible builds.
The \f[CR]\-\-fakemachine\-backend=kvm\f[R] option is specified to
ensure KVM is used as expected:
.IP
.EX
jobs\f[B]:\f[R]
  build\f[B]:\f[R]
    runs\-on\f[B]:\f[R] ubuntu\-latest
    container\f[B]:\f[R]
      image\f[B]:\f[R] ghcr.io/go\-debos/debos:main
      options\f[B]:\f[R] \-\-device=/dev/kvm
    steps\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] uses\f[B]:\f[R] actions/checkout\(atv4
      \f[B]\-\f[R] run\f[B]:\f[R] debos \-\-fakemachine\-backend=kvm \-\-print\-recipe recipe.yaml
.EE
.SH INSTALLATION FROM SOURCE
.SS DEPENDENCIES
Debian:
.IP
.EX
sudo apt install golang git libglib2.0\-dev libostree\-dev qemu\-system\-x86 \(rs
     qemu\-user\-static debootstrap systemd\-container
.EE
.PP
Arch Linux:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# pipewire\-jack is used to satisfy the jack dependency required by qemu\-full,\f[R]
\f[I]# alternatively jack2 can be used instead.\f[R]
sudo pacman \-S \-\-needed base\-devel pkgconf go git glib2 ostree \(rs
     gobject\-introspection debootstrap qemu\-full qemu\-user\-static \(rs
     systemd pipewire\-jack
.EE
.SS INSTALL
.IP
.EX
export GOPATH=/opt/src/gocode \f[I]# or whatever suits your needs\f[R]

go install \-v github.com/go\-debos/debos/cmd/debos\(atlatest

/opt/src/gocode/bin/debos \-\-help
.EE
.SH SIMPLE EXAMPLE
The following example will create an arm64 image, install several
packages in it, change the file \f[CR]/etc/hostname\f[R] to
\f[CR]debian\f[R] and finally make a tarball of the complete system.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]{\- $image := or .image \(dqdebian.tgz\(dq \-\f[B]}\f[R]}

architecture\f[B]:\f[R] arm64

actions\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] debootstrap
    suite\f[B]:\f[R] trixie
    components\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] main
      \f[B]\-\f[R] non\-free\-firmware
    mirror\f[B]:\f[R] https://deb.debian.org/debian
    variant\f[B]:\f[R] minbase

  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] apt
    packages\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] sudo
      \f[B]\-\f[R] openssh\-server
      \f[B]\-\f[R] adduser
      \f[B]\-\f[R] systemd\-sysv
      \f[B]\-\f[R] firmware\-linux

  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] run
    chroot\f[B]:\f[R] true
    command\f[B]:\f[R] echo debian > /etc/hostname

  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] pack
    file\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]{ $image \f[B]}\f[R]}
    compression\f[B]:\f[R] gz
.EE
.PP
To run it, create a file named \f[CR]example.yaml\f[R] and run:
.IP
.EX
debos example.yaml
.EE
.PP
The final tarball will be named \f[CR]debian.tgz\f[R].
If you would like to modify the fileame, you can provide a different
name for the variable image like this:
.IP
.EX
debos \-t image:\(dqdebian\-arm64.tgz\(dq example.yaml
.EE
.SH RECIPE SYNTAX
A recipe is a YAML file.
Before it is parsed as YAML it is run through the Golang \c
.UR https://pkg.go.dev/text/template
template engine
.UE \c
, so a recipe is effectively a template that produces YAML.
A recipe has two parts: \- a header \- a list of actions.
.PP
Recipe comments should start with \f[CR]#\f[R].
.SS RECIPE HEADER
The recipe header may contain the following properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]architecture\f[R] \(en target architecture (string).
Mandatory; debos aborts if it is missing (e.g.\ \f[CR]amd64\f[R] or
\f[CR]arm64\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]sectorsize\f[R] \(en logical sector size in bytes (integer).
Optional, defaults to \f[CR]512\f[R].
Set this to \f[CR]4096\f[R] for devices using 4K blocks such as some UFS
or NVMe storage.
It is consumed by the \f[CR]image\-partition\f[R] and \f[CR]raw\f[R]
actions.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]actions\f[R] \(en the list of actions to run.
Mandatory; at least one action is required.
.PP
A minimal example for a recipe:
.IP
.EX
architecture\f[B]:\f[R] arm64
sectorsize\f[B]:\f[R] 512

actions\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] debootstrap
    suite\f[B]:\f[R] trixie
.EE
.SS RECIPE TEMPLATE VARIABLES
Two kinds of variables are passed to the recipe and they use different
syntax:
.IP \(bu 2
Variables passed on the command line with \f[CR]\-t NAME:VALUE\f[R] are
fields of the template data object and are referenced in the recipe as
\f[CR]{{ .NAME }}\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Local variables are declared inside the recipe with
\f[CR]{{ $name := \(dqvalue\(dq }}\f[R] and referenced as
\f[CR]{{ $name }}\f[R].
.PP
The common idiom combines both to give a command\-line variable a
default:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]{\- $image := or .image \(dqdebian.tgz\(dq \-\f[B]}\f[R]}

architecture\f[B]:\f[R] arm64

actions\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] pack
    file\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]{ $image \f[B]}\f[R]}
.EE
.PP
Here \f[CR]debos recipe.yaml\f[R] creates \f[CR]debian.tgz\f[R], while
\f[CR]debos \-t image:custom.tgz recipe.yaml\f[R] creates
\f[CR]custom.tgz\f[R].
.PP
The \f[CR]recipe\f[R] action passes variables injected with
\f[CR]\-t NAME:VALUE\f[R] down to the included recipe.
The \f[CR]architecture\f[R] property of an included recipe must match
the parent and is injected automatically as a template variable.
.SS RECIPE TEMPLATE FUNCTIONS
In addition to the standard Go template functions and the \c
.UR https://go-task.github.io/slim-sprig/
slim\-sprig
.UE \c
\ function library, the following custom functions are available:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]escape\f[R] \(en shell\-escape the argument,
e.g.\ \f[CR]{{ escape $var }}\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]uuid5\f[R] \(en generate a deterministic version 5 UUID,
\f[CR]{{ uuid5 $namespace $data }}\f[R].
\f[CR]$namespace\f[R] must be a valid UUID.
Passing fixed values produces a reproducible UUID, which may be useful
for the image\-partition action.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]sector\f[R] \(en appends an \f[CR]s\f[R] suffix,
e.g.\ \f[CR]{{ sector 256 }}\f[R] becomes \f[CR]256s\f[R].
Deprecated: the sector size is unknown at templating time, so write the
offset directly as \f[CR]256s\f[R] and let the action resolve it from
\f[CR]sectorsize\f[R].
.PP
Use \f[CR]\-\-print\-recipe\f[R] to print the recipe after templating
and \f[CR]\-\-dry\-run\f[R] to compose and verify the recipe without
performing any work.
.SH RECIPE ACTIONS
Actions are executed in the order they are listed in the recipe.
Unless \f[CR]\-\-disable\-fakemachine\f[R] is given (or no backend is
available), all actions run inside the fakemachine virtual machine.
The actions are grouped below by purpose.
.PP
Each action accepts two common properties in addition to the
action\-specific ones listed below:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]action\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Selects the action to run; it must be one of the actions documented
below.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]description\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Free\-text label shown in debos output for this action; defaults to the
action name.
.PP
Only the action\-specific properties are listed in each action\(cqs
section.
.PP
The following actions construct the target root filesystem.
.SS \f[CR]DEBOOTSTRAP\f[R] ACTION
Construct the target rootfs with the \f[CR]debootstrap\f[R] tool.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]suite\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Release code name or symbolic name (e.g.
\f[CR]trixie\f[R], \f[CR]stable\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]mirror\f[R] \(en string, optional, default
\f[CR]http://deb.debian.org/debian\f[R].
A Debian\-compatible repository URL.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]variant\f[R] \(en string, optional.
debootstrap variant to use, e.g.\ \f[CR]minbase\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]components\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional, default
\f[CR][main]\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]keyring\-package\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Keyring package validating the repository.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]keyring\-file\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Keyring file validating the repository (path relative to the recipe
directory).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]certificate\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Client certificate file.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]private\-key\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Client private key file.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]merged\-usr\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
Create a merged\-\f[CR]/usr\f[R] filesystem.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]check\-gpg\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
Verify the repository GPG signature.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] debootstrap
  suite\f[B]:\f[R] trixie
  components\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] main
    \f[B]\-\f[R] non\-free\-firmware
  mirror\f[B]:\f[R] https://deb.debian.org/debian
  variant\f[B]:\f[R] minbase
.EE
.PP
Notes: \f[CR]/etc/resolv.conf\f[R] is removed after the bootstrap
because debootstrap copies it from the host.
For a foreign architecture the second stage runs in the chroot.
.SS \f[CR]MMDEBSTRAP\f[R] ACTION
Construct the target rootfs with the \f[CR]mmdebstrap\f[R] tool.
Compared to \f[CR]debootstrap\f[R] it can install extra packages and
accept arbitrary apt/dpkg options during the bootstrap.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]suite\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]mirrors\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
Debian\-compatible repository URLs.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]variant\f[R] \(en string, optional.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]components\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional, default
\f[CR][main]\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]keyring\-packages\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]keyring\-files\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
Paths relative to the recipe directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]merged\-usr\f[R] \(en bool, optional.
If unset the distribution default is used (this differs from
\f[CR]debootstrap\f[R], where the default is \f[CR]true\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]include\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
Packages to install during the bootstrap.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]dpkg\-opts\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
Arbitrary dpkg options.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]apt\-opts\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
Arbitrary apt options.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] mmdebstrap
  suite\f[B]:\f[R] trixie
  mirrors\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] https://deb.debian.org/debian
  variant\f[B]:\f[R] minbase
  include\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] ca\-certificates
  apt\-opts\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] \-oAcquire::Languages=none
.EE
.PP
Notes: \f[CR]/etc/resolv.conf\f[R] is removed after the bootstrap.
.SS \f[CR]PACSTRAP\f[R] ACTION
Construct an Arch Linux target rootfs with the \f[CR]pacstrap\f[R] tool.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]config\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
\f[CR]pacman.conf\f[R] file, relative to the recipe directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]mirror\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
mirrorlist file, relative to the recipe directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]packages\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
If empty only the \f[CR]base\f[R] metapackage is installed.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] pacstrap
  config\f[B]:\f[R] files/pacman.conf
  mirror\f[B]:\f[R] files/mirrorlist
  packages\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] base
    \f[B]\-\f[R] linux
    \f[B]\-\f[R] openssh
.EE
.PP
Notes: this action requires fakemachine; it fails with
\f[CR]\-\-disable\-fakemachine\f[R].
.PP
The following actions install packages into an existing rootfs.
.SS \f[CR]APT\f[R] ACTION
Install packages and their dependencies into the target rootfs with
\f[CR]apt\f[R].
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]packages\f[R] \(en list of strings, mandatory.
Packages to install.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]recommends\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]false\f[R].
Install recommended packages.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]unauthenticated\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default
\f[CR]false\f[R].
Allow unauthenticated packages.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]update\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
Run \f[CR]apt update\f[R] before installing.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] apt
  recommends\f[B]:\f[R] false
  packages\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] openssh\-server
    \f[B]\-\f[R] sudo
    \f[B]\-\f[R] systemd\-sysv
.EE
.SS \f[CR]PACMAN\f[R] ACTION
Install packages and their dependencies into an Arch Linux rootfs with
\f[CR]pacman\f[R].
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]packages\f[R] \(en list of strings, mandatory.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] pacman
  packages\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] vim
    \f[B]\-\f[R] sudo
.EE
.SS \f[CR]INSTALL\-DEB\f[R] ACTION
Install local \f[CR].deb\f[R] packages and their dependencies into the
target rootfs using \f[CR]apt\f[R].
Dependencies are resolved from the configured apt sources.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]origin\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the recipe directory.
The named origin (see \f[I]The origin property\f[R]) containing the
packages.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]packages\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
\f[CR].deb\f[R] files or glob patterns resolved within
\f[CR]origin\f[R].
May be omitted when \f[CR]origin\f[R] refers to a single downloaded
file.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]recommends\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]false\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]unauthenticated\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default
\f[CR]false\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]update\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
.PP
Origin behavior: when \f[CR]origin\f[R] is a directory,
\f[CR]packages\f[R] selects files within it (glob patterns allowed).
When \f[CR]origin\f[R] is a single file produced by a
\f[CR]download\f[R] action, omit \f[CR]packages\f[R].
.PP
Example \(en install local packages shipped with the recipe:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] install\-deb
  packages\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] pkgs/*.deb
    \f[B]\-\f[R] pkgs/bmap\-tools_*_all.deb
.EE
.PP
Example \(en download a \f[CR].deb\f[R] and install it with its
dependencies:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] download
  url\f[B]:\f[R] http://example.com/foo_1.0_all.deb
  name\f[B]:\f[R] foo\-deb

\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] install\-deb
  origin\f[B]:\f[R] foo\-deb
.EE
.PP
The following actions add files to the target filesystem.
.SS \f[CR]DOWNLOAD\f[R] ACTION
Download a single file from the internet and optionally unpack it.
The download is registered as a named origin for use by later actions.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]url\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
\f[CR]http\f[R] or \f[CR]https\f[R] URL.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]name\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Origin name exported for later actions.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]filename\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Output file name; derived from the URL when omitted.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]unpack\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]false\f[R].
Extract the archive after download.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]compression\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Compression hint for \f[CR]unpack\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]sha256sum\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Expected SHA256 sum (exactly 64 hex characters); verified after
download.
.PP
Origin behavior: the origin named by \f[CR]name\f[R] resolves to the
downloaded file, or, when \f[CR]unpack\f[R] is \f[CR]true\f[R], to the
extraction directory (\f[CR]<filename>.d\f[R]).
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] download
  url\f[B]:\f[R] https://example.com/rootfs.tar.gz
  name\f[B]:\f[R] rootfs
  sha256sum\f[B]:\f[R] 0123...cdef
  unpack\f[B]:\f[R] true
  compression\f[B]:\f[R] gz

\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] overlay
  origin\f[B]:\f[R] rootfs
.EE
.SS \f[CR]OVERLAY\f[R] ACTION
Recursively copy a file or directory tree into the target filesystem,
preserving permissions and extended attributes.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]origin\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the recipe directory.
Source origin (see \f[I]The origin property\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]source\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Path relative to \f[CR]origin\f[R].
If empty the origin root is used.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]destination\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the rootfs root.
Absolute path inside the target filesystem.
.PP
At least one of \f[CR]source\f[R] or \f[CR]origin\f[R] must be set.
.PP
Origin behavior: \f[CR]origin\f[R] is resolved through the origin map.
When \f[CR]origin\f[R] is empty or \f[CR]recipe\f[R], \f[CR]source\f[R]
must exist on disk at verification time.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] overlay
  source\f[B]:\f[R] overlays/sudo
.EE
.PP
This copies \f[CR]overlays/sudo/etc/sudoers.d/user\f[R] from the recipe
directory to \f[CR]/etc/sudoers.d/user\f[R] in the rootfs.
.SS \f[CR]UNPACK\f[R] ACTION
Unpack a (optionally compressed) tar archive into the target filesystem.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]origin\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the artifact directory.
Origin containing the archive.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]file\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Archive file name within \f[CR]origin\f[R].
May be omitted when \f[CR]origin\f[R] is a single downloaded file.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]destdir\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the rootfs root.
Destination path inside the target filesystem.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]compression\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Compression hint; auto\-detected from the file extension when omitted.
.PP
At least one of \f[CR]file\f[R] or \f[CR]origin\f[R] must be set.
.PP
Origin behavior: by default the archive is looked up in the artifact
directory; set \f[CR]origin\f[R] to a \f[CR]download\f[R] name to unpack
a downloaded archive.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] unpack
  origin\f[B]:\f[R] artifacts
  file\f[B]:\f[R] rootfs.tar.gz
  destdir\f[B]:\f[R] /
.EE
.PP
The following actions create and populate the output image.
.SS \f[CR]IMAGE\-PARTITION\f[R] ACTION
Create an image file, partition it and format the filesystems.
Mountpoints can be defined so partitions are mounted during the build
and, by default, mounted at boot in the final system.
Mountpoints are sorted by their position in the filesystem hierarchy, so
their order in the recipe does not matter.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]imagename\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Output image file, relative to the artifact directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]imagesize\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Image size in human\-readable form, e.g.
\f[CR]100MB\f[R], \f[CR]4GB\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partitiontype\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
\f[CR]gpt\f[R] or \f[CR]msdos\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]diskid\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Disk identifier; GUID format for \f[CR]gpt\f[R], a 32\-bit hex value (no
dashes) for \f[CR]msdos\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]gpt_gap\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Shift the GPT to leave a gap for a bootloader (\f[CR]gpt\f[R] only;
requires parted support).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partitions\f[R] \(en list, mandatory.
At least one partition (see below).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]mountpoints\f[R] \(en list, optional.
Mountpoints (see below).
.SS PARTITION PROPERTIES
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]name\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Unique; used to reference the partition from mountpoints and
\f[CR]raw\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]fs\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Filesystem type (\f[CR]ext4\f[R], \f[CR]btrfs\f[R], \f[CR]f2fs\f[R],
\f[CR]xfs\f[R], \f[CR]hfs\f[R], \f[CR]hfsplus\f[R],
\f[CR]vfat\f[R]/\f[CR]fat*\f[R], \&...).
Use \f[CR]none\f[R] for a partition without a filesystem.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]start\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Start offset from the beginning of the disk; human readable
(\f[CR]32MB\f[R]) or percentage (\f[CR]0%\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]end\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
End offset; same format as \f[CR]start\f[R] (\f[CR]100%\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partlabel\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the partition
\f[CR]name\f[R].
GPT partition label (\f[CR]gpt\f[R] only).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]fslabel\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the partition
\f[CR]name\f[R].
Filesystem label.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]parttype\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Partition type; 2\-char hex for \f[CR]msdos\f[R], 36\-char GUID for
\f[CR]gpt\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partattrs\f[R] \(en list, optional.
GPT partition attribute bits.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partuuid\f[R] \(en string, optional.
GPT partition UUID (e.g.\ from \f[CR]uuid5\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]fsuuid\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Filesystem UUID (btrfs, ext2/3/4, xfs).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]flags\f[R] \(en list, optional.
parted(8) \f[CR]set\f[R] flags, e.g.\ \f[CR][ boot ]\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]features\f[R] \(en list, optional.
Extra filesystem features to enable.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]extendedoptions\f[R] \(en list, optional.
Extra filesystem extended options.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]fsck\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
When \f[CR]false\f[R], sets \f[CR]fs_passno\f[R] to \f[CR]0\f[R] (no
boot\-time check).
.SS MOUNTPOINT PROPERTIES
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partition\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
A partition \f[CR]name\f[R] defined above.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]mountpoint\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Unique path in the target filesystem.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]options\f[R] \(en list, optional.
fstab options for this entry.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]buildtime\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]false\f[R].
Mount only during the debos run; no \f[CR]/etc/fstab\f[R] entry is
created and the directory is removed from the image.
.PP
Example \(en two\-partition msdos image (FAT firmware + ext4 root):
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] image\-partition
  imagename\f[B]:\f[R] debian\-rpi3.img
  imagesize\f[B]:\f[R] 1GB
  partitiontype\f[B]:\f[R] msdos
  mountpoints\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] mountpoint\f[B]:\f[R] /
      partition\f[B]:\f[R] root
    \f[B]\-\f[R] mountpoint\f[B]:\f[R] /boot/firmware
      partition\f[B]:\f[R] firmware
      options\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R] x\-systemd.automount \f[B]]\f[R]
  partitions\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] firmware
      fs\f[B]:\f[R] vfat
      start\f[B]:\f[R] 0%
      end\f[B]:\f[R] 64MB
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] root
      fs\f[B]:\f[R] ext4
      start\f[B]:\f[R] 64MB
      end\f[B]:\f[R] 100%
      flags\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B][\f[R] boot \f[B]]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
The partition device paths are recorded by name so the \f[CR]raw\f[R]
action can write to a specific partition.
.SS \f[CR]FILESYSTEM\-DEPLOY\f[R] ACTION
Deploy the prepared root filesystem onto the image created by a previous
\f[CR]image\-partition\f[R] action, and optionally generate
\f[CR]/etc/fstab\f[R] and the kernel command line.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]setup\-fstab\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
Generate \f[CR]/etc/fstab\f[R] from the partition layout.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]setup\-kernel\-cmdline\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default
\f[CR]true\f[R].
Add the root partition to \f[CR]/etc/kernel/cmdline\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]append\-kernel\-cmdline\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Extra kernel command line arguments.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] filesystem\-deploy
  setup\-fstab\f[B]:\f[R] true
  setup\-kernel\-cmdline\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.PP
Notes: a previous \f[CR]image\-partition\f[R] action is required.
Afterwards the build operates on the mounted image
(\f[CR]context.Rootdir\f[R] and the \f[CR]filesystem\f[R] origin point
at the mounted image), so later actions modify the image directly.
.SS \f[CR]RAW\f[R] ACTION
Directly write a file into the output image at a given offset.
Typically used for bootloaders.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]source\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
File to write into the image.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]origin\f[R] \(en string, optional, default the recipe directory.
Origin containing \f[CR]source\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]offset\f[R] \(en string, optional, default \f[CR]0\f[R].
Offset in bytes, or in sectors with an \f[CR]s\f[R] suffix
(e.g.\ \f[CR]256s\f[R]); the sector size comes from the recipe
\f[CR]sectorsize\f[R] header.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]partition\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Named partition to write to; if unset the whole image is used.
.PP
Origin behavior: \f[CR]origin\f[R] is resolved through the origin map.
The deprecated \f[CR]path\f[R] property and the deprecated
\f[CR]{{ sector N }}\f[R] template function still work but should be
replaced by \f[CR]origin\f[R]/\f[CR]source\f[R] and a literal
\f[CR]Ns\f[R] offset.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] raw
  origin\f[B]:\f[R] recipe
  source\f[B]:\f[R] files/u\-boot.bin
  offset\f[B]:\f[R] 8192s
.EE
.PP
The following actions integrate OSTree.
.SS \f[CR]OSTREE\-COMMIT\f[R] ACTION
Create an OSTree commit from the root filesystem.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]repository\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
OSTree repository path, relative to the artifact directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]branch\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
OSTree branch name.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]subject\f[R] \(en string, optional.
One\-line commit description.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]collection\-id\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Collection ID for ref binding (requires libostree 2018.6+).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]ref\-binding\f[R] \(en list of strings, optional.
Branches the commit must be retrieved from.
Defaults to \f[CR][branch]\f[R] when \f[CR]collection\-id\f[R] is set.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]metadata\f[R] \(en map of string to string, optional.
Commit metadata.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] ostree\-commit
  repository\f[B]:\f[R] repo
  branch\f[B]:\f[R] debian/trixie
  subject\f[B]:\f[R] Debian trixie
.EE
.SS \f[CR]OSTREE\-DEPLOY\f[R] ACTION
Deploy an OSTree branch into the image.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]repository\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Local OSTree repository, relative to the artifact directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]remote_repository\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
URL of the remote OSTree repository (remote pull is currently not
implemented; use a local repository).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]branch\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Branch to deploy.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]os\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
OSTree OS deployment name.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]setup\-fstab\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]true\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]setup\-kernel\-cmdline\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default
\f[CR]true\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]append\-kernel\-cmdline\f[R] \(en string, optional.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]tls\-client\-cert\-path\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Client certificate for the remote repository.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]tls\-client\-key\-path\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Client certificate key.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]collection\-id\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Collection ID ref binding (requires libostree 2018.6+).
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] ostree\-deploy
  repository\f[B]:\f[R] repo
  remote_repository\f[B]:\f[R] http://localhost/repo
  branch\f[B]:\f[R] debian/trixie
  os\f[B]:\f[R] debian
.EE
.PP
Notes: a previous \f[CR]image\-partition\f[R] action is required.
.PP
The following action archives the root filesystem.
.SS \f[CR]PACK\f[R] ACTION
Create a tarball from the root filesystem.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]file\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Output tarball, relative to the artifact directory.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]compression\f[R] \(en string, optional, default \f[CR]gz\f[R].
One of \f[CR]bzip2\f[R], \f[CR]gz\f[R], \f[CR]lzip\f[R],
\f[CR]lzma\f[R], \f[CR]lzop\f[R], \f[CR]xz\f[R], \f[CR]zstd\f[R],
\f[CR]auto\f[R], \f[CR]none\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]subdir\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Subdirectory within the rootfs to archive (must exist); defaults to the
whole rootfs.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] pack
  file\f[B]:\f[R] rootfs.tar.gz
  compression\f[B]:\f[R] gz
.EE
.PP
Notes: \f[CR]pigz\f[R] is used automatically for \f[CR]gz\f[R]
compression when available.
.PP
The following actions control execution flow.
.SS \f[CR]RECIPE\f[R] ACTION
Include the actions of another recipe, optionally overriding template
variables.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]recipe\f[R] \(en string, mandatory.
Path to the recipe to include (relative to the current recipe
directory).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]variables\f[R] \(en map of string to string, optional.
Template variables passed to the included recipe.
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] recipe
  recipe\f[B]:\f[R] partition.yaml
  variables\f[B]:\f[R]
    imagesize\f[B]:\f[R] 4GB
.EE
.PP
Notes: the included recipe\(cqs \f[CR]architecture\f[R] must match the
parent and is injected automatically.
Only one \f[CR]image\-partition\f[R] action may exist across the
combined recipes.
.SS \f[CR]RUN\f[R] ACTION
Run a command or a script, either in the build host environment (the
fakemachine) or in the target filesystem.
.PP
Properties:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]command\f[R] \(en string.
A command line, or \(en using a YAML block scalar
(\f[CR]command: |\f[R]) \(en a multi\-line shell script.
The command(s) must be available in the host or chroot environment.
Mutually exclusive with \f[CR]script\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]script\f[R] \(en string.
Script with arguments; the script must be located in the recipe
directory.
Mutually exclusive with \f[CR]command\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]chroot\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]false\f[R].
Run inside the target filesystem instead of the build host.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]postprocess\f[R] \(en bool, optional, default \f[CR]false\f[R].
Run after all other actions, with the artifact directory as working
directory.
Mutually exclusive with \f[CR]chroot\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]label\f[R] \(en string, optional.
Label used for output; derived from the command/script (truncated at 40
characters) when empty.
.PP
One of \f[CR]command\f[R] or \f[CR]script\f[R] is required.
The command or script is run with root privileges via
\f[CR]sh \-e \-c\f[R].
Because \f[CR]command\f[R] is passed to the shell as a single string, a
YAML block scalar (\f[CR]command: |\f[R]) may contain several commands
on separate lines: they run as one script, the first line is used as the
output label, and \(en because of the \f[CR]\-e\f[R] flag \(en execution
stops at the first command that fails.
.PP
Environment variables: debos exports the following variables to
non\-chroot \f[CR]run\f[R] actions.
Inside a chroot the command runs in the target\(cqs own environment and
debos does not inject these (a \f[CR]script\f[R] is bind\-mounted to
\f[CR]/tmp/script\f[R]).
\f[CR]postprocess\f[R] runs outside the chroot.
.PP
