\f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] run
  postprocess\f[B]:\f[R] true
  command\f[B]:\f[R] gzip \-f {{ $image }}
.EE
.SH OTHER EXAMPLE RECIPES
The doc/examples directory contains a complete, runnable example recipe
ospack\-debian.yaml which builds a minimal Debian tarball.
.PP
Further more detailed example recipes are stored under the \c
.UR https://github.com/go-debos/debos-recipes
debos\-recipes
.UE \c
\ repository.
.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.SS HOST\-PROPAGATED VARIABLES
debos reads a predefined list of environment variables from the host and
propagates them to the fakemachine build environment.
The list is defined by \f[CR]environVars\f[R] in
\f[CR]cmd/debos/debos.go\f[R] and currently covers the proxy variables
documented at https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/proxy_settings:
.IP
.EX
http_proxy, https_proxy, ftp_proxy, rsync_proxy, all_proxy, no_proxy
.EE
.PP
For each of the above variables, both the lower and upper case variant
is probed on the host and, if found, propagated to fakemachine
preserving the case.
So, if the host defines \f[CR]HTTP_PROXY\f[R] and \f[CR]no_proxy\f[R],
both are propagated as\-is.
.SS SETTING AND OVERRIDING VARIABLES
The \f[CR]\-\-environ\-var\f[R] and \f[CR]\-e\f[R] options specify,
overwrite or unset environment variables for fakemachine:
.IP
.EX
debos \-e ENVIRONVAR:VALUE ...
.EE
.PP
To unset a variable (e.g.\ prevent it from being propagated to
fakemachine) use the same syntax without a value.
Multiple \f[CR]\-e\f[R] options may be given.
.SS PROXY CONFIGURATION CAVEATS
While the proxy variables are exported from the host to fakemachine,
there are two known sources of issues:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]localhost\f[R] will not work from fakemachine.
Use an address that is valid on your network.
debos warns if a variable contains \f[CR]localhost\f[R],
\f[CR]127.0.0.1\f[R] or \f[CR]::1\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Applications and scripts run inside fakemachine may expect differently
named or differently cased proxy variables; check which variables they
use.
.SS VARIABLES EXPOSED TO THE RUN ACTION
The \f[CR]run\f[R] action exposes \f[CR]RECIPEDIR\f[R],
\f[CR]ARTIFACTDIR\f[R], \f[CR]ROOTDIR\f[R], \f[CR]IMAGEMNTDIR\f[R] and
\f[CR]IMAGE\f[R] to non\-chroot commands and scripts.
Which variables are set depends on \f[CR]chroot\f[R] and
\f[CR]postprocess\f[R]; see the table in the \f[I]run\f[R] action above.
.SS ORIGINS
Several actions accept an \f[CR]origin\f[R] property that selects where
their input comes from.
The following origins are always available:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]recipe\f[R] \(en the directory the recipe is in.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]filesystem\f[R] \(en the target filesystem root.
Set by \f[CR]filesystem\-deploy\f[R] and \f[CR]ostree\-deploy\f[R] to
the mounted image after deployment.
